### Short answer: 

It is because of the order in which these methods work. The `Funtion#andThen` method works opposite of the `Function#compose` method.

### Details:

[`Funtion#andThen`](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/util/function/Function.html#andThen-java.util.function.Function-) documentation:

&gt; Returns a composed function that first applies this function to its
&gt; input, and then applies the **after function** to the result.

[`Function#compose`](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/util/function/Function.html#compose-java.util.function.Function-) documentation:

&gt; Returns a composed function that first applies the before function to
&gt; its input, and then applies **this function** to the result.

So in the case of `Funtion#andThen`, the type inference of arguments is already available to the compiler while in the second case (i.e. `Function#compose`) it is not.

By the way, I prefer to use `compose` this way:

    import java.util.function.Function;
    
    public class Main {
    	public static void main(String[] args) {
    		Function&lt;String, String&gt; test = (s) -&gt; s.concat(&quot;foo&quot;);
    		Function&lt;String, String&gt; upper = String::toUpperCase;    
    		String str = test.compose(upper).apply(&quot;bar&quot;);
            //...
    	}
    }

Here&#39;s [an example](http://www.oracle.com/webfolder/technetwork/tutorials/obe/java/basic_app_embedded_tomcat/basic_app-tomcat-embedded.html).&lt;br&gt;
It shows a simple webpage with bootstrap front-end integrated with java-backend service.&lt;br&gt;
Or in another [post](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/15189437/twitter-bootstrap-with-spring-mvc) it mentions integrate bootstrap with spring.

